He actually was a waterworks.

279
00:18:36,900 --> 00:18:39,410
- Geez. 
 - But that guy, Mr. Ha!

280
00:18:39,410 --> 00:18:42,400
Isn't he culpable as well?

281
00:18:42,400 --> 00:18:44,410
He should've bought something that could get listed.

282
00:18:44,410 --> 00:18:46,950
He left me with something that wasn't going to work.

283
00:18:46,950 --> 00:18:48,600
He spoke as if he had nothing to do with it.

284
00:18:48,600 --> 00:18:51,060
He's so annoying!

285
00:18:51,060 --> 00:18:53,380
I'll see what I can do

286
00:18:53,380 --> 00:18:54,850
so calm down for now.

287
00:18:54,850 --> 00:18:58,440
Honestly, Mr. Lee, this is...

288
00:18:58,440 --> 00:19:00,810
my second year now.

289
00:19:00,810 --> 00:19:03,260
Because of my contract renewal,

290
00:19:03,260 --> 00:19:07,200
I worked so hard on the Saipan project.

291
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:09,140
And out of nowhere...

292
00:19:09,140 --> 00:19:11,490
Wind? Goodness.

293
00:19:11,490 --> 00:19:15,150
The market sentiment is key to an IPO, right?

294
00:19:15,150 --> 00:19:17,510
Listing Wind wouldn't be an issue if things looked up,

295
00:19:17,510 --> 00:19:19,570
but it was so bad lately that

296
00:19:19,570 --> 00:19:22,210
it needs to show that it'd get better.

297
00:19:22,210 --> 00:19:24,760
But Wind's sales actually declined.

298
00:19:24,760 --> 00:19:27,360
That's why you had to give a negative report.

299
00:19:27,360 --> 00:19:31,860
Yes. If I reported that it'd succeed when it likely won't,

300
00:19:31,860 --> 00:19:34,240
we'd be doomed.

301
00:19:34,240 --> 00:19:35,820
You did the right thing.

302
00:19:35,820 --> 00:19:37,960
What are the terms of our option with PPF?

303
00:19:37,960 --> 00:19:40,170
Looking at our put option with PPF,

304
00:19:40,170 --> 00:19:42,160
Sanin's stock price has to stay below 100,000 won

305
00:19:42,160 --> 00:19:44,600
for 20 consecutive trading days.

306
00:19:44,600 --> 00:19:47,510
So that's how it works.

307
00:19:47,510 --> 00:19:49,900
Twenty trading days are four weeks.

308
00:19:49,900 --> 00:19:53,250
Then we should just raise the stock price in four weeks.

309
00:19:53,250 --> 00:19:54,620
How?

310
00:19:54,620 --> 00:19:58,430
By getting Wind listed?

311
00:19:58,430 --> 00:20:01,240
 If it were that easy, we would've done it already. 

312
00:20:01,240 --> 00:20:06,430
It's ended up like this because he kept pushing off telling the chairman.

313
00:20:07,690 --> 00:20:09,290
Yes.

314
00:20:11,190 --> 00:20:12,560
Gosh...

315
00:20:12,560 --> 00:20:16,620
It's really tough to say something isn't going to work.

316
00:20:16,620 --> 00:20:20,040
Who could say that?

317
00:20:20,040 --> 00:20:24,240
If you speak up like that, you'd only get criticized.

318
00:20:24,890 --> 00:20:28,010
This is like hot potatoes.

319
00:20:28,010 --> 00:20:31,180
That's a good way to put it. Hot potatoes.

320
00:20:33,020 --> 00:20:35,180
Come, let's go.

321
00:20:35,180 --> 00:20:36,500
Chairman.

322
00:20:37,150 --> 00:20:38,030
The chairman is leaving.

323
00:20:38,030 --> 00:20:39,160
Should I get the car ready?

324
00:20:39,160 --> 00:20:41,690
- Hey, let's go over there. 
 - Pardon?

325
00:20:41,690 --> 00:20:43,710
What floor is the team leader on?

326
00:20:43,710 --> 00:20:45,400
Oh, he's on the 13th floor.

327
00:20:45,400 --> 00:20:46,580
Let's go.

328
00:20:46,580 --> 00:20:49,670
But there are many bicycles around Han River.

329
00:20:49,670 --> 00:20:51,560
Yes, there are quite a lot.

330
00:20:51,560 --> 00:20:53,330
So how come Wind didn't sell?

331
00:20:53,330 --> 00:20:55,410
There are more shared bikes now.

332
00:20:55,410 --> 00:20:59,390
I see. Aren't those nearly all free?

333
00:21:00,200 --> 00:21:02,900
All the bicycle companies will go down. I mean...

334
00:21:02,900 --> 00:21:05,710
how can you beat a government-run business?

335
00:21:05,710 --> 00:21:08,100
I don't intend to beat them.

336
00:21:09,830 --> 00:21:12,390
No, no, it's all right.

337
00:21:13,250 --> 00:21:14,490
You heard the news, right?

338
00:21:14,490 --> 00:21:18,080
If you're referring to Wind, I read the article.

339
00:21:18,080 --> 00:21:19,330
Okay.

340
00:21:19,330 --> 00:21:21,790
What are your thoughts?

341
00:21:21,790 --> 00:21:24,320
I thought it'd be difficult from the start.

342
00:21:24,320 --> 00:21:27,440
You all think it won't work, right?

343
00:21:27,440 --> 00:21:30,350
But did everything fail when COVID hit?

344
00:21:30,350 --> 00:21:33,040
Some places did well despite the fact.

345
00:21:33,040 --> 00:21:34,100
Am I wrong?

346
00:21:34,100 --> 00:21:38,230
You're right. But even if COVID didn't hit,

347
00:21:38,230 --> 00:21:40,640
the bicycle market wouldn't have done well.

348
00:21:40,640 --> 00:21:42,310
What do you mean by that?

349
00:21:42,310 --> 00:21:46,120
With the rise of shared bikes, more people started riding bikes

350
00:21:46,120 --> 00:21:49,290
but most bike companies have poor performance.

351
00:21:49,290 --> 00:21:50,620
You're right.

352
00:21:50,620 --> 00:21:52,850
The government is giving free access to bikes.

353
00:21:52,850 --> 00:21:54,380
So who'd buy one?

354
00:21:54,380 --> 00:21:56,270
They did that with tax money.

355
00:21:56,270 --> 00:21:57,940
How could we beat that? Isn't that right?

356
00:21:57,940 --> 00:22:01,120
Yes, so there needs to be an incentive

357
00:22:01,120 --> 00:22:05,100
to make bike riders want to ride better bikes.

358
00:22:05,100 --> 00:22:07,410
With such an incentive,

359
00:22:07,410 --> 00:22:11,500
I think the high-end market could actually improve.

360
00:22:12,270 --> 00:22:13,940
Then...

361
00:22:15,660 --> 00:22:18,120
do you think you can do it?

362
00:22:23,560 --> 00:22:24,900
Well?

363
00:22:25,490 --> 00:22:27,030
Yes.

364
00:22:31,790 --> 00:22:33,990
The CEO used to be an archery athlete.

365
00:22:33,990 --> 00:22:39,600
He started with archery before transitioning into cycling with his expertise in carbon materials.

366
00:22:39,600 --> 00:22:41,520
So he's only dealt with making carbon bikes,

367
00:22:41,520 --> 00:22:44,390
leading him to focus on the high-end market.

368
00:22:47,170 --> 00:22:50,030
You don't have any questions?

369
00:22:50,030 --> 00:22:52,330
Why did you say you can do it?

370
00:22:52,330 --> 00:22:54,970
All we had to do was stay quiet. Tell me.

371
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:57,280
Why did you do it?

372
00:22:57,280 --> 00:22:59,700
Because I felt like it would work.

373
00:23:00,380 --> 00:23:02,940
I'm used to it by now.

374
00:23:05,450 --> 00:23:09,390
   

375
00:23:22,100 --> 00:23:24,230
Hello. Welcome.

376
00:23:24,230 --> 00:23:25,410
I'm Park Rae Gyeong.

377
00:23:25,410 --> 00:23:27,650
Hi. Nice to meet you.

378
00:23:30,340 --> 00:23:35,790
We've displayed the archery equipment we've made in order.

379
00:23:35,790 --> 00:23:41,280
The photos are a collection of important and meaningful moments.

380
00:23:41,280 --> 00:23:45,200
During the Olympics, forget everything else, I always watch archery.

381
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:48,420
Hitting the bullseye is impressive already,

382
00:23:48,420 --> 00:23:51,290
but it's amazing to hit a 10-point shot.

383
00:23:51,290 --> 00:23:53,170
How do they do it?

384
00:23:53,170 --> 00:23:54,600
Are they born with it?

385
00:23:54,600 --> 00:23:57,190
You can do it with enough practice.

386
00:23:57,190 --> 00:24:00,480
Still, don't you need natural talent?

387
00:24:00,480 --> 00:24:02,710
You do need a natural talent.

388
00:24:02,710 --> 00:24:08,080
But keeping on doing something is important than doing it well.

389
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:09,730
You were an athlete, too, right?

390
00:24:09,730 --> 00:24:12,990
I wasn't that great as an athlete.

391
00:24:12,990 --> 00:24:14,770
I didn't win any medals.

392
00:24:14,770 --> 00:24:17,420
But these bows won gold medals for me.

393
00:24:17,420 --> 00:24:21,420
Then you've won too many medals, right?

394
00:24:23,770 --> 00:24:28,010
This was when we acquired Daichi.

395
00:24:28,010 --> 00:24:30,780
Daichi used to be the number one company, right?

396
00:24:30,780 --> 00:24:32,400
Back in the 1990s, it was.

397
00:24:32,400 --> 00:24:36,020
But we acquired them after we surpassed them.

398
00:24:36,020 --> 00:24:39,150
Who's the person next to you?

399
00:24:40,980 --> 00:24:44,100
He's the one who drew this blueprint.

400
00:24:44,100 --> 00:24:47,550
He was Daichi's best technician.

401
00:24:47,550 --> 00:24:51,200
Then did this artisan give you this blueprint?

402
00:24:51,200 --> 00:24:52,760
Yes, as a gift.

403
00:24:52,760 --> 00:24:55,150
And I gave him this slogan as a gift.

404
00:24:55,150 --> 00:24:58,290
Did you do this brush calligraphy yourself?

405
00:24:58,290 --> 00:25:00,270
When I used to do archery,

406
00:25:00,270 --> 00:25:04,220
I thought it'd help with focusing, so I dabbled in it.

407
00:25:06,010 --> 00:25:07,330
What does it say?

408
00:25:07,330 --> 00:25:09,040
"On Go Ji Sin."

409
00:25:09,040 --> 00:25:12,670
"Learn the old, understand the new."

410
00:25:13,460 --> 00:25:15,460
He's a cutie.

411
00:25:15,460 --> 00:25:16,910
   

412
00:25:16,910 --> 00:25:20,160
He's the artisan's son he had in later years.

413
00:25:20,160 --> 00:25:22,860
He was so cute.

414
00:25:27,270 --> 00:25:31,160
From here on, it's all bikes.

415
00:25:33,010 --> 00:25:35,650
How much is a bike like this one?

416
00:25:36,320 --> 00:25:38,880
It's about 30 million won.

417
00:25:39,950 --> 00:25:42,380
The bike is more expensive than a car.

418
00:25:42,380 --> 00:25:43,520
Indeed.

419
00:25:43,520 --> 00:25:45,910
I thought it'd be about one million won at most.

420
00:25:45,910 --> 00:25:48,190
That's because this is for professional athletes.

421
00:25:48,190 --> 00:25:49,770
Oh, I see.

422
00:25:49,770 --> 00:25:53,720
The fact that athletes ride Wind bikes is a testament to the quality, right?

423
00:25:53,720 --> 00:25:55,140
Of course.

424
00:25:55,140 --> 00:25:59,600
Athletes bet their lives on 0.1 or 0.01 seconds

425
00:25:59,600 --> 00:26:02,610
so they won't ride it unless it's the best.

426
00:26:02,610 --> 00:26:07,210
But selling only to athletes would limit your sales.

427
00:26:08,320 --> 00:26:10,810
Well, that's the issue.

428
00:26:10,810 --> 00:26:14,330
It's something Wind has to solve.

429
00:26:14,330 --> 00:26:18,170
Let's solve... that issue together.

430
00:26:18,170 --> 00:26:19,620
   

431
00:26:20,400 --> 00:26:24,440
Wind has released 12 models ranging from five million to 30 million won.

432
00:26:24,440 --> 00:26:27,900
You'd think the five million won model would sell the most,

433
00:26:27,900 --> 00:26:30,360
but surprisingly, it sold the least.

434
00:26:30,360 --> 00:26:33,140
Sports are all about competition, right?

435
00:26:33,140 --> 00:26:35,750
The same goes for equipment.

436
00:26:35,750 --> 00:26:39,040
Nobody likes being last.

437
00:26:39,040 --> 00:26:44,840
That's why the model that's one tier above the cheapest model, Wind-A, sold the most.

438
00:26:44,840 --> 00:26:46,490
Yes.

439
00:26:46,490 --> 00:26:48,720
That's the nature of sports.

440
00:26:48,720 --> 00:26:50,800
Nobody likes being last.

441
00:26:50,800 --> 00:26:55,460
What if Wind-A isn't last then?

442
00:26:55,460 --> 00:26:57,180
Pardon?

443
00:27:00,050 --> 00:27:03,270
Bicycles are ranked based on the material.

444
00:27:03,270 --> 00:27:04,480
That's right.

445
00:27:04,480 --> 00:27:07,610
It's steel, aluminum, then carbon.

446
00:27:07,610 --> 00:27:11,970
To go from a competitor's aluminum model to Wind's carbon, it's an additional one million won.

447
00:27:11,970 --> 00:27:18,140
That extra million creates a barrier that prevents people from upgrading from aluminum to carbon.

448
00:27:21,930 --> 00:27:25,620
Carbon is on a completely different level.

449
00:27:25,620 --> 00:27:28,420
It's not even worth comparing it to aluminum.

450
00:27:28,420 --> 00:27:29,590
Right.

451
00:27:29,590 --> 00:27:34,060
What if we could sell Wind-A, on another level, for around four million won?

452
00:27:34,060 --> 00:27:36,680
In this competition with aluminum bikes

453
00:27:36,680 --> 00:27:38,870
wouldn't we be sure to win?

454
00:27:38,870 --> 00:27:40,810
We'd win for sure.

455
00:27:40,810 --> 00:27:43,780
Absolutely. For the same price, nobody would pick aluminum.

456
00:27:43,780 --> 00:27:45,650
They'd choose carbon.

457
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:51,010
Yes. Then, naturally, we can bring in

458
00:27:51,010 --> 00:27:53,860
aluminum consumers to Wind.

459
00:27:55,320 --> 00:27:56,830
Well...

460
00:27:58,570 --> 00:28:01,110
I agree,

461
00:28:01,110 --> 00:28:06,890
but matching the price point isn't easy.

462
00:28:06,890 --> 00:28:10,180
Even the five million won price was a real stretch,

463
00:28:10,180 --> 00:28:13,580
so four million won is really tough.

464
00:28:14,490 --> 00:28:16,730
What if the market grows?

465
00:28:16,730 --> 00:28:19,920
Wouldn't we be able to mass produce then?

466
00:28:19,920 --> 00:28:21,490
We would.

467
00:28:21,490 --> 00:28:26,240
But in the bicycle industry, it's not just about the frame.

468
00:28:26,240 --> 00:28:28,970
The gears are really important.

469
00:28:28,970 --> 00:28:32,040
Shimizu in Japan is the best for that.

470
00:28:32,040 --> 00:28:34,520
They hold the patents, too.

471
00:28:34,520 --> 00:28:36,230
They need to provide us with the gears.

472
00:28:36,230 --> 00:28:40,330
If they don't, we can't mass produce, even if we want to.

473
00:28:40,330 --> 00:28:42,280
It's like semiconductors.

474
00:28:42,280 --> 00:28:43,790
That's right.

475
00:28:43,790 --> 00:28:46,080
Shimizu is essentially the top player.

476
00:28:46,080 --> 00:28:48,980
It'll be hard to get more supply from them.

477
00:28:48,980 --> 00:28:53,430
We'll meet with Shimizu and negotiate that.

478
00:28:56,220 --> 00:29:00,330
If so, we need it resolved by next week

479
00:29:00,330 --> 00:29:03,100
because we have an OEM contract lined up.

480
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:07,300
In that case, we'll need to go immediately.

481
00:29:08,490 --> 00:29:10,880
Mr. Yun, this is my first overseas deal.

482
00:29:10,880 --> 00:29:13,500
Is there anything I should watch out for?

483
00:29:13,500 --> 00:29:18,240
It's important to respect the rules of that country, since we're the visitors.

484
00:29:18,240 --> 00:29:21,160
Wouldn't that be too disadvantageous for us?

485
00:29:21,160 --> 00:29:23,240
That's not always true.

486
00:29:23,240 --> 00:29:25,700
Both sides have to follow the rules,

487
00:29:25,700 --> 00:29:27,650
so we won't be at a disadvantage

488
00:29:27,650 --> 00:29:32,590
as long as we know what those rules are.

489
00:29:32,590 --> 00:29:34,900
   

490
00:30:04,850 --> 00:30:06,560
Yes?

491
00:30:07,900 --> 00:30:09,560
Hey.

492
00:30:09,560 --> 00:30:11,210
Come in.

493
00:30:13,750 --> 00:30:15,560
- Take a seat. 
 - Okay.

494
00:30:15,560 --> 00:30:17,960
Did you come from Wind?

495
00:30:17,960 --> 00:30:19,460
Yes.

496
00:30:20,130 --> 00:30:23,780
I feel like I've just passed the burden onto you.

497
00:30:23,780 --> 00:30:24,960
Don't feel that way.

498
00:30:24,960 --> 00:30:28,200
I heard you've already tried it once, Mr. Lee.

499
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:32,200
Yumin IB said you tried to get it listed,

500
00:30:32,200 --> 00:30:35,740
but you stopped after receiving a negative report.

501
00:30:35,740 --> 00:30:37,370
Yes.

502
00:30:38,340 --> 00:30:41,950
Since Wind focused on the high-end market,

503
00:30:41,950 --> 00:30:44,800
scalability was an issue.

504
00:30:45,380 --> 00:30:48,760
That's why I thought nothing could be done.

505
00:30:50,240 --> 00:30:53,780
But after hearing what you said to the chairman...

506
00:30:54,780 --> 00:30:56,760
I was ashamed.

507
00:30:56,760 --> 00:30:58,160
No, don't be.

508
00:30:58,160 --> 00:31:02,820
Also, that article was written by a reporter who's connected to me.

509
00:31:02,820 --> 00:31:04,860
Reporter Han Ji Eun?

510
00:31:04,860 --> 00:31:05,790
Yes.

511
00:31:05,790 --> 00:31:11,550
When I was acquiring Cha Cha Games, she wrote an article about Sanin and DC in an M&amp;A.

512
00:31:11,550 --> 00:31:14,210
She asked me about it.

513
00:31:14,210 --> 00:31:15,770
I see.

514
00:31:15,770 --> 00:31:18,400
That's why I need to resolve this issue.

515
00:31:18,400 --> 00:31:21,470
It's also something Project M needs to handle.

516
00:31:22,640 --> 00:31:28,150
As you've said, the market sentiment for bike companies isn't good.

517
00:31:28,150 --> 00:31:30,380
Speed is the largest company in Korea, right?

518
00:31:30,380 --> 00:31:32,090
Among the bike companies, yes.

519
00:31:32,090 --> 00:31:34,500
They probably had a large supply of gears.

520
00:31:34,500 --> 00:31:38,600
Yes, but they've put it on hold after paying a penalty.

521
00:31:38,600 --> 00:31:41,270
The timing is a bit of a shame.

522
00:31:41,270 --> 00:31:43,020
Speed was disappointed as well.

523
00:31:43,020 --> 00:31:45,320
If they knew sooner, they wouldn't have paid the penalty

524
00:31:45,320 --> 00:31:48,020
and sold the excess gears to Wind.

525
00:31:48,020 --> 00:31:49,640
Yes.

526
00:31:50,250 --> 00:31:53,530
Aigoo, you should get going now.

527
00:31:53,530 --> 00:31:55,780
- See you later, then. 
 - All right.

528
00:31:57,040 --> 00:31:58,830
What is that?

529
00:31:58,830 --> 00:32:02,270
I found it while looking up Japanese business words.

530
00:32:02,270 --> 00:32:04,820
Have you heard of "honne" and "tateme"?

531
00:32:04,820 --> 00:32:05,910
Of course, I have.

532
00:32:05,910 --> 00:32:07,770
You're referring to using cushion words, right?

533
00:32:07,770 --> 00:32:09,250
Yes.

534
00:32:09,250 --> 00:32:12,030
Attorney, you're so smart.

535
00:32:12,030 --> 00:32:14,730
Now, you finally recognize it.

536
00:32:15,950 --> 00:32:18,120
But it was "honne"?

537
00:32:18,120 --> 00:32:22,330
You can lower the unit price if you increase the quantity.

538
00:32:25,640 --> 00:32:29,630
Supposedly, Japanese people hate changing plans.

539
00:32:31,120 --> 00:32:34,000
Even if we're buying tenfold? Why wouldn't they like it?

540
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:37,300
That's understandable since they go by the book.

